Changes:
- add internal `_curryN` function, similar to `op` but capable of currying functions of arbitrary arity;
- define `curryN` as `_curryN(2, _curryN)`;
- update `_checkForMethod` to return a function with the appropriate arity;
- replace occurrences of `_curry2`, `_curry3`, and `op` with `curry`; and
- remove `_curry2`, `_curry3`, and `op`.

Reasons to like these changes:
- it will put an end to ad hoc pull requests adding "op-style" currying to one or two functions at a time;
- it improves consistency‚úù;
- partial application is not _only_ useful for binary functions;
- it removes the distinction between "operator" functions and other functions, simplifying Ramda's mental model and making `R.__` easier to explain; and
- it further promotes partial application, Ramda's key feature.

Reasons to dislike these changes:
- it's a breaking change‚úù‚úù; and
- it increases the amount of work required to apply a curried function.

‚úù Currently commutative functions do not support `R.__`, as it's not useful. For consistency, though, they should. One could then say that `R.curry(f)(R.__, b)(a)` is equivalent to `f(a, b)` for any binary function `f`, in the same way one can currently say that `R.curry(f)(a)(b)` is equivalent to `f(a, b)` for any binary function `f`. (All the discussion in Fantasy Land seems to have got me thinking in terms of laws and whatnot.)

‚úù‚úù Currently `R.divide(R.__)` is equivalent to `R.flip(R.divide)`, which has always seemed to me like too much magic. I doubt anyone is using this form, as the `R.flip` version is much clearer.

@buzzdecafe and I discussed this change and decided it's a good idea for two reasons:
- it's one of the few (or perhaps the only) Ramda function with an optional argument; and
- it's unnecessary, since `R.of(42, Id)` can be written as `Id.of(42)`.

